- ## Objectives
#Objectives #DevOps 
Steffens et al. [5] opine that DevOps is a pipeline as well as a  piece of software and DevOps has characteristics of a process. It  is a practice that aims at merging development, quality assurance,  and operations (deployment and integration) into a single,  continuous set of processes. In a corporate study [6], a Team Lead  (Infrastructure) (TLI) described DevOps as “a blend of skills and  knowledge of operation and development with maximum  collaboration and communication”, while a Release Quality  Leader defined it as “a kind of hands-on, short-term and longer-  term situation where everybody’s working really closely,  communicating really closely, and getting an understanding of  where everything’s at so they’re not just two very segregated  departments [anymore]”. In the same study, the Operation  Manager highlighted that DevOps is all about supporting “more  natural communications with the people around you”.  DevOps integrates separated development and operations teams  into a single agile unit. The integration promises faster  development and deployment of more reliable software with  testing interwoven into each build cycle. As per the Annual  Quality Report 2016-17 [7] published by Capgemini, 88% of the  companies surveyed has used or experimented with DevOps  principles. As per the reports, most seem to be at the beginning of  their DevOps journeys. This is further corroborated by the survey  results, where the proportion of organizations using DevOps for  less than 20% of their projects has risen from just 7% in 2015 to  47% in 2017. - ## Challenges
#Challenges #DevOps 
Perera [12] has highlighted many benefits of DevOps such as  closed communication across teams, increment frequency of  software releases, high understanding to business needs and better  code quality and reliability. However, the methodology does  suffer from various challenges that hinder it from going  mainstream [6].  From the literature, the key challenges hindering the adoption of  DevOps can be classified into following key segments - People  and Culture, Misunderstanding, Security, Process and  Technology. In a study that assigned the count value to each  factors, people, culture and lack of understanding of DevOps were  revealed to be the main challenges that exist when compared to  other factors. For example, resistance to change due to fear of loss  of job/ business is a long-standing people and culture issue.  Another challenge is the siloed practices of business that occurs  when business units do not interact with each other until  necessary. This disconnection is typically created because of the  lack of desire to work outside the drawn business areas which has  formed naturally when certain groups of people may not like to  work with each other. A sense of responsibility is another people  and culture challenge, which highlights that developers were not  found to show accountability for the deployment of the software  or a product which makes further harder to adopt DevOps.  Another challenge is the misunderstanding that occurs when IT  organizations tries to adopt DevOps with a prescriptive  methodology or a big expensive all-in-one DevOps technology.  Finally, process and technology challenge highlight another area  of research: how to re-engineer the schism that exists between  development and operations processes. This clearly indicates that  DevOps is not a just technology or service that can be downloaded  (from an open source or vendor) and can be used to fasten the  software development life cycle process. There is a need to clearly  understand and address the DevOps for its effective and less risky  adoption [4].Continuous Delivery Benefits and Challenges  Existing studies have shown that the processes themselves are the  main obstacles in adopting CD. Chen has reported there were  some process challenges in his study [13]. For example, most  large organizations have many protocols (read processes), that  must be followed, to release a unit of software in production. In  worst case scenarios, an engineer at some large enterprises may  need to provide more than a hundred different documents and  follow numerous processes to release any code change to  production. Even worse, these processes could take several weeks  or even months. Such lengthy processes have prevented companies from adopting CD. What complicates the matters even  more is the fact that CD were originally put in place to ensure  quality and security. In fact, many organizations have employed people whose sole job is to ensure that everyone follows the  official processes.  Shanin et. al. [14] found that the deployment process in some  organizations is still highly bureaucratic. A bureaucratic process  can be characterized as the one having many formal tasks (e.g.,  getting approvals from various people) to be performed manually  before each release. - ## Continuous
#Continuous #Delivery #Development #Interest #Classification #ValueBased #Software #Engineering #Software #Engineering 
Continuous Delivery (CDE) is a  collection of practices that targets to deliver value to customers  swiftly, reliably and repeatedly with less manual process. The  deployment pipeline is the core part of CDE. Humble and Farley  [8] described the term as an automated exhibition of the process  for obtaining software from version control into the end-users., i.e.  the deployment pipeline is a software system that automates the  software delivery process. In other places, they defined the  deployment pipeline as a model (the process modeled by the  deployment pipeline). Bass et al. [9] describes the same  dimensions: first, the DevOps pipeline itself is a component of  software, and second, the DevOps pipeline has features of a  process.

In many cases, testing cannot be carried out until after the code  has been compiled, deployed and run in a production-like  environment. In such environments, testing the deployed code  may be delayed due to various factors, including server  configuration, requirement of production size systems for load and  performance tests. A deployment process triggered automatically  bypassing these factors also referred to as the “Quality Gates”,  would make it easier to deploy more often. When cloud  computing resources are integrated into the automatic deployment  process, the deployment process will become a regular affair,  rather than a step taken only late in the development lifecycle.  This system would allow delivery pipeline progress without  human interaction.
